      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Experiments show that 50% of an oral 100-mg dose of Drug A is absorbed in a 60-kg test subject. However, the fractional bioavailability was only 0.2. Assuming a liver blood flow of 1500 mL/min, which of the following is the hepatic clearance of Drug A in this situation?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q6675207",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 35858,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        4
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Ans. D) 900 mL/min</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Let us do the calculations based on the given Information:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">This question can be solved by two methods.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Method 1- by using the formula</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Dose</strong> = 100 mg</span><br>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Fraction absorbed (F_abs)</strong> = 0.5</span><br>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Fractional bioavailability (F)</strong> = 0.2</span><br>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Liver blood flow (Q)</strong> = 1500 mL/min</span><br>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Systemic bioavailability(F)=Fractional absorption*(1–Extraction ratio)</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">0.2=0.5×(1−ER)</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">0.4=1-ER</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">ER=0.6</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Now, hepatic clearance is calculated as:</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">clearance=ER*Hepatic blood flow</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">=0.6*1500ml/min</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">=900ml/min</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Method 2- by using the conceptual knowledge.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ol><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Absorption and Bioavailability</strong>:</span><ul><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>50% of the 100 mg dose</strong>&nbsp;of Drug A is absorbed, so&nbsp;<strong>50 mg</strong>&nbsp;reaches the liver.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">The&nbsp;<strong>fractional bioavailability (F)</strong>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<strong>0.2</strong>, meaning&nbsp;<strong>20%</strong>&nbsp;of the absorbed drug reaches the&nbsp;<strong>systemic circulation</strong>, or&nbsp;<strong>20 mg</strong>.</span></li></ul></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Amount Extracted by the Liver</strong>:</span><ul><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>50 mg</strong>&nbsp;of the absorbed drug reaches the liver, and&nbsp;<strong>20 mg</strong>&nbsp;exits into the systemic circulation.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">Therefore, the&nbsp;<strong>amount extracted by the liver</strong>&nbsp;is: 50 mg − 20  mg = 30 mg</span></li></ul></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Hepatic Extraction Ratio (ER)</strong>:</span><ul><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">The&nbsp;<strong>hepatic extraction ratio</strong>&nbsp;is the&nbsp;<strong>fraction of the drug extracted by the liver</strong>:</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">ER = Amount&nbsp;extracted&nbsp;by&nbsp;the&nbsp;liver/Amount&nbsp;reaching&nbsp;the&nbsp;liver&nbsp;= 30 mg / 50 mg = 0.6</span></li></ul></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Hepatic Clearance (Clₕ)</strong>:</span><ul><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">Hepatic clearance is given by the formula:</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">CL = Liver&nbsp;Blood&nbsp;Flow&nbsp;(Q) × Extraction&nbsp;Ratio&nbsp;</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">Given that the&nbsp;<strong>liver blood flow (Q)</strong>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<strong>1500 mL/min</strong>&nbsp;(or 1.5 L/min) and the&nbsp;<strong>extraction ratio (ER)</strong>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<strong>0.6</strong>:</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">CL = 1500 mL/min × 0.6 = 900 mL/min</span></li></ul></li></ol><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective</u></strong><u>:</u></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">To calculate the <strong>hepatic clearance of a drug</strong>, apply the formula <strong>hepatic clearance = hepatic extraction ratio × hepatic blood flow,</strong> using the<strong> fraction of the drug </strong>dose <strong>absorbed and the fractional bioavailability</strong> to determine the <strong>extraction ratio</strong>.&nbsp;</span></p>",
